      "url": "http://www.heraldbulletin.com/news/local_news/event-to-focus-on-women-veterans/article_98212f3c-3003-5538-9248-fdcedd224f93.html",
      "host": "heraldbulletin.com",
      "text": "Event to focus on women veterans Breakfast, author talk to be featured Tuesday By Devan Filchak The Herald Bulletin Oct 22, 2017 \nANDERSON — Thanking them for their service and providing resources will be the main objectives of a free event for women veterans in Anderson on Tuesday. \nHosted by Easterseals Crossroads, a United Way agency, it will include breakfast and an appearance by Indianapolis Mobile Vet Center. \nThe event runs from 8:30 until 11 a.m. at the Salvation Army, 1615 Meridian St.. \nAndrea Carlile, author of “The War that Came Home,” is guest speaker. Carlile also contributed to “When War Comes Home,” a documentary about how war affects families. \nThe organization will hold two similar events in Indianapolis next week as well: one Wednesday at the Lincoln Square Pancake House and one Thursday at the Fort Harrison Veterans Center. Each event will have a different guest speaker. \nSince the Tuesday event is in Anderson, the focus will be on resources available in Madison County, said Buzz Smith, veteran resource navigator at Easterseals Crossroads. Making sure the veterans are in the Veterans Affairs system and receiving proper benefits will be part of the event as well. \nSmith said the organization holds what it calls rally point events that are essentially veterans resource fairs. However, he said it’s important to have an event specifically focused on women veterans. \n“We feel that female veterans really don’t get enough press or glory,” he said. “We just don’t think they are recognized as much as the male veteran counterparts. Basically that’s what this is — a recognition and thank you.” \nIf you go \nWhat: Event for women veterans \nWhen: 8:30 to 11 a.m. Tuesday \nWhere: Salvation Army, 1615 Meridian St., Anderson. \nCost: Free and includes breakfast Tags",
