      "host": "howiecarrshow.com",
      "text": "Baker, O’Donnell undeserving of Gold Star attention By tweet Massachusetts Governor Charlie Baker speaks at the Senate Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions Committee hearing to discuses ways to stabilize health insurance markets​, on Capitol Hill in Washington, Thursday, Sept. 7, 2017. ( AP Photo/Jose Luis Magana) \nGov. Charlie Baker loves words that start with the letter “d”, and not just the one that he should have already embraced, which is “Democrat.” \nIn case you missed it, the Republican In Name Only (RINO) governor took yet another swipe at Donald Trump on Thursday, saying he found the president’s telephone conversation with a Florida Gold Star widow “incredibly disgraceful and discouraging and depressing.” \nNaturally, Tall Deval has no idea what was actually said in the conversation, or the context, but he’s… distressed, you might say. It used to be that Baker was merely “disappointed” in the president, but as the 2018 election nears, he’s upped the decibel level, to dust off another “d” word. \nA year ago, before the presidential election, he smugly announced that he would be blanking the top line on the ballot. This, Faker Baker declared to various reporters, was either “hugely disappointing” or “extremely disappointing.” \nSince the inauguration, the House’s vote to repeal Obamacare has “disappointed” him, while Trump’s decision to pull out of the Paris climate accord left the governor “very disappointed.” \nTo be fair, for Tall Deval, disappointment comes from every political direction. Obama’s decision last year on the offshore “national-monuments” designation “deeply disappointed” him. At the State House, he has found both declining state tax revenues and hack state-college presidents walking away with $335,000 cash payouts to be “disappointing.” A decision to let corrupt pols keep their ill-gotten state pensions left Tall Deval “extremely disappointed.” \nIn June I wrote about Charlie’s string of disappointing disappointments, and he subsequently dialed back his use of his favorite “d” word, although the president’s statements about Charlottesville in August “deeply disappointed” the depressed demi-Democrat. \nBut I think this latest denunciation of the president is a harbinger of things to come in Tall Deval’s upcoming campaign. And may I suggest another “d” word for the Baker reelection effort – “disgust.” It’s already in his dictionary for dummies—a year ago he found the president “not only inappropriate but outrageous and disgusting.” \nRemember that word, disgusting. You read it here first. \nTall Deval, of course, went to Harvard, and you know that ancient axiom: “You can always tell a Harvard man, but you can’t tell him much.” \nHarvard’s motto used to start with a “V” – Veritas – and it still does, only now the phrase is “Virtue Signaling.” \nCharlie’s not the only Harvard man in public life living up to the V phrase. How about Lawrence O’Donnell, ’74, five years ahead of Tall Deval? \nIn case you missed it, and I’m guessing you did, the tough street kid from St. Seb’s went off on a rant this week on MSNBC, and this time he wasn’t slurring Mormons or screaming, “Stop the hammering!” at a blue-collar studio work crew. \nThis time O’Donnell was trying to class-shame Trump’s chief of staff, John Kelly, for his defense of the president. Sounding like a busing-era bow-tied swell from Brookline or Lincoln, O’Donnell sniffed that he “knows” Oak Square, Brighton, which Kelly came out of, because he comes from an “identical” neighborhood. \nReally? Kelly’s father was a mailman, O’Donnell’s a lawyer. In the early 70’s, as O’Donnell was adjusting his cravat, sipping brandies Alexander and tossing off precious bon mots in the Harvard Lampoon, Kelly was serving in the U.S. Marine Corps. Yeah, they have identical backgrounds all right. \nO’Donnell also said that Kelly went to “segregated schools.” The future general graduated the now-closed St. Mary’s High School in Waltham – if O’Donnell is accusing the Christian Brothers of being racists, that’s an even more scurrilous attack than he made against the Mormons a few years back. \nAnd for that matter, how many blacks were in the St. Sebastian’s Class of ’70? \nBy the way, I’m sure that when Trump was going after the Gold Star father Khizr Khan last year, O’Donnell was slamming the future president as the worst person in the world. But now O’Donnell casually dismisses a different Gold Star father as a racist, even though he knows absolutely nothing about Kelly, let alone what’s in his heart. \nBut lifelong pampered puke O’Donnell isn’t engaging in hate speech, he’s speaking truth to power. Just ask him. The PC hypocrisy here – not to mention the classism – is so thick you could cut it with a knife. \nI’ll bet Lawrence O’Donnell loves Charlie Baker. They have so much in common. Dim dismal Democrat demagogues. SHARE Howie Carr Howie Carr is the New York Times best-selling author of The Brothers Bulger and Hitman, in addition to several other Boston organized-crime books and two novels. He is the host of a New England-wide radio talk-show syndicated to more than 20 stations, and is a member of the Radio Hall of Fame in Chicago.",
