      "title": "Allen P. Osmundson, 81 | Obituaries | wahpetondailynews.com",
      "country": "US",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T04:30:14Z",
      "url": "http://www.wahpetondailynews.com/obituaries/allen-p-osmundson/article_fad44ef6-b5e2-11e7-99cc-1bbd6406e905.html",
      "host": "wahpetondailynews.com",
      "text": "0 \nAllen P. Osmundson, 81, of Glen Ullin, formerly of Fergus Falls, Minnesota, passed away Sunday, Oct. 15, 2017 at Sanford Health in Bismarck, North Dakota. \nA memorial service will be held at 2 p.m. Sunday, Oct., 29, 2017 at Faith Lutheran Church in Dwight, North Dakota. \nAllen Paul Osmundson was born June 24, 1936 in Breckenridge, Minnesota, to Art and Palma Osmundson of Dwight. He graduated from Wahpeton High School and then went to the North Dakota State College of Science. He served in the military. Allen was in the Army National Guard for two years and the U.S. Army for three years. While in the Army he drove truck until he received his sharpshooter medal. He was then employed as a shooting instructor. From there he became Military Police and was stationed in Honolulu, Hawaii. \nWhile in Hawaii, he met Patricia Maile Sylva. He received an honorable discharge and came home to North Dakota where they were married Oct. 31, 1958 in Dwight. Their son, Curtis, was born Sept. 7, 1959. \nFor several years, Al had his own apiary, where he produced honey and other bee products. He lived in North Dakota for many years and was known as “the bee man.” He also lived in South Dakota, Minnesota, Louisiana,and Texas. During these years he drove truck for other beekeepers. Later in life he lived in Fergus Falls where he could be closer to his son Curtis and his wife Milly, and his granddaughter, Ellie. \nOne thing Al may be remembered for is he didn’t know a stranger. He was friendly and liked to visit with everyone. He also enjoyed hunting and fishing. He liked to watch the Minnesota Twins baseball or boxing on TV. \nHe is preceded in death by his parents, Art and Palma; a special aunt, Olga Paulson; his brother, Lyle Osmundson; and his nephew Corey. \nHe is survived by his son, Curtis (Milly); granddaughter, Ellie (Jesse) Tomford; great-grandson, Liam, sister-in-law, Carol Osmundson; nephew Jeff (Pam) Osmundson and family; and niece Kimbra (Dave) Amerman and family. \nBlessed be the memory of Allen Osmundson. \nStevenson Funeral Home & Crematory in Dickinson is in charge of the arrangements. Tags",
