      "host": "bizjournals.com",
      "text": "35 photos ALBANY: New York's capital city might not be Amazon's first thought for its HQ2. But economic development officials there say they plan to be aggressive in pursuing the project. “We will work with CEG and others to develop a proposal for Amazon,” says Marty Vanags, president of… more Amazon is still building out… more Anthony Bolante | PSBJ – Dallas Business Journal Oct 23, 2017, 2:25pm CDT Amazon.com said its call for second headquarters proposals received 238 bids from cities and regions in 54 states and provinces across North America. The Seattle-based internet retailer and cloud computing giant launched its contest for a $5 billion, 50,000-employee \"HQ2\" in September. Amazon asked North American governments to submit bids for the campus including infrastructure data, demographics and potential subsidies. The window to submit proposals closed Thursday. Amazon said the bids include 43 U.S. states, plus the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico. The only U.S. states not represented in the bids were Arkansas, Hawaii, Montana, North Dakota, South Dakota, Vermont and Wyoming. Dallas-Fort Worth submitted a unified bid that included at least 35 sites in a dozen North Texas cities . The proposal highlighted the region's business-friendly climate, cost of living and an undisclosed amount of economic incentives. “Our goal is not to win the project with this RFP and this response,” said Brandom Gengelbach, executive vice president of economic development for the Fort Worth Chamber of Commerce. “Our goal is to get into the ‘yes’ pile, and know that there will probably another one, two or three rounds, and to let Amazon know we stand willing and ready and able to make that next step.” Other HQ2 hopefuls used gimmicks to try to lure Amazon. A city council in Georgia voted to de-annex 345 acres of land and ask the state to rename it \"the city of Amazon\" if the company chooses the site for HQ2. Tuscon, Arizona sent a 21-foot saguaro cactus to Seattle as a gift. Calgary, Alberta covered the company's Seattle campus with sidewalk chalk. Amazon's HQ2 seems to promise economic development for the winning city in the form of high-paying jobs, real estate deals and a vibrant technology ecosystem. It's also likely to raise rents and increase traffic. The company said it plans to announce a second headquarters next year. Through hundreds of interviews and public records requests , The Business Journal recently detailed Amazon's playbook for expanding the distribution network that's key to the internet retailer's continued growth. Amazon is still building out… more Anthony Bolante | PSBJ",
