      "host": "nj.com",
      "text": "Heavy rain, strong thunderstorms, damaging wind to lash N.J. Posted October 24, 2017 at 06:36 AM | Updated October 24, 2017 at 06:40 AM By Len Melisurgo | NJ Advance Media for NJ.com IMG_2381.JPG \nNew Jerseyans could face a challenging commute to and from work on Tuesday, with heavy rain and strong thunderstorms expected to sweep through the region as a slow-moving cold front rumbles in from the Midwest and brings an end to the long stretch of dry weather. \nMore than 20,000 residents were already without power as of 6:30 a.m. from high wind overnight. \nAlthough severe weather is not usually welcome, this one could erase the sizable October rainfall deficit and help boost the region’s drinking water supplies. \nMost areas of New Jersey, New York City and eastern Pennsylvania have received very little rain this month, just off the heels of a fairly dry September. Newark's rainfall total this month is almost 2 inches below normal, and New York City is running a rainfall deficit of more than 2 inches, according to data from the National Weather Service . \nTuesday's rain storms, which could linger into Wednesday morning, are forecast to bring 1 to 2 inches of rain to most regions of New Jersey and 2 to 2.5 inches to New York City, with higher amounts possible in the strongest thunderstorms. Wind advisories and some early-morning power outages \nA wind advisory is in effect for all but the five northeastern counties (Bergen, Essex, Hudson, Passaic and Union) on Tuesday morning. Winds out of the south of 10 to 20 mph could gust as high as 45 mph. The strongest winds are expected to occur before 9 a.m., the weather service said early Tuesday. \nAs of 6:15 a.m., Atlantic City Electric had more than 14,000 customers without power, primarily in Gloucester County. PSE&G had more than 4,000 customers without power. Most of those were in Burlington and Camden Counties. JCP&L (First Energy) reported nearly 1,200 residents without power with most of those in Burlington and Monmouth counties. rain-forecast-oct23-oct25-nj.jpg \nThis map shows the total rainfall projections for most of New Jersey and other parts of the Mid-Atlantic region through early Thursday afternoon. (National Weather Service | Middle Atlantic River Forecast Center)",
